{"title_page": "Christina Hendricks", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Christina Hendricks\n| image              = Christina Hendricks at PaleyFest 2014.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Hendricks at the 2014 [[Paley Center for Media|PaleyFest]] for ''[[Mad Men]]''\n| birth_name         = Christina Rene Hendricks\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1975|05|03}}\n| birth_place        = [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]], [[Tennessee]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actress|model}}\n| years_active       = 1999\u2013present\n| height             = {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/christina-hendricks-measurements-too-big-for-hollywood/|work=[[CBS News]]|title=Christina Hendricks' Measurements - Too Big for Hollywood?|last=Hunter|first=Aina|date=September 21, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217202329/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/christina-hendricks-measurements-too-big-for-hollywood/|archive-date=December 17, 2013}}</ref>\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Geoffrey Arend]]|2009|2019|reason={{abbr|sep.|separated}}}}\n| home_town          = [[Twin Falls, Idaho]], U.S.\n}}\n\n'''Christina Rene Hendricks''' (born May 3, 1975)<ref>{{cite web|title=About Christina Hendricks|url=https://www.vogue.in/topics/christina-hendricks|work=[[Vogue India]]|accessdate= July 5, 2018}}</ref> is an American actress and former model. Her accolades include six [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations, two [[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s, and two [[Critics' Choice Television Award|Critics' Choice Awards]] for [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Drama Series|Best Supporting Actress in a Drama Series]]. A 2010 poll of female readers taken by ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' magazine named her \"the sexiest woman in the world,\"<ref name=\"esquireApril20\" /> and voted as Best Looking Woman in America the same year.<ref name=\"esquireApril20\">{{cite web |title= The Esquire Survey of the American Woman |url= http://www.esquire.com/women/women-issue/survey-of-american-women-0510/ |work= Esquire|date= April 20, 2010 |accessdate= May 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Welles |first= Denmark |url= http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/62338,people,entertainment,christina-hendricks-voted-best-looking-woman-in-us-esquire-mad-men |title= Mad Men's Christina Hendricks voted best-looking woman in US &#124; People |work=The First Post |date=April 23, 2010 |accessdate=February 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBorn in Tennessee, Hendricks was raised in [[Portland, Oregon]] and [[Twin Falls, Idaho]], where she became active in local theater. After completing high school in [[Virginia]], Hendricks relocated to New York City and pursued a career as a model following her entry into a ''[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]'' cover contest. She continued to work internationally as a model for over a decade before transitioning into acting.\n\nHendricks had recurring roles in several television series, including ''[[Beggars and Choosers (TV series)|Beggars and Choosers]]'' (2001\u20132002) and ''[[Kevin Hill]]'' (2004\u20132005) before being cast as [[Joan Holloway]] on the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] period drama series ''[[Mad Men]]'' in 2007, of which she remained a main cast member until the series' conclusion in 2015. She received critical acclaim for her role on the series, including six Emmy Award nominations and multiple Screen Actors Guild Awards for Best Ensemble. While starring on ''Mad Men'', Hendricks also began appearing in films, receiving critical notice for her performance in [[Nicolas Winding Refn]]'s thriller ''[[Drive (2011 film)|Drive]]'' (2011), [[Sally Potter]]'s drama ''[[Ginger & Rosa]]'' (2012), and [[Ryan Gosling]]'s neo-noir fantasy ''[[Lost River (film)|Lost River]]'' (2014).\n\nFollowing the conclusion of ''Mad Men'', Hendricks starred in the comedy series ''[[Another Period]]'' from 2015 to 2016, and in the [[SundanceTV]] drama series ''[[Hap and Leonard (TV series)|Hap and Leonard]]'' (2016). She reunited with Refn for a supporting role in his thriller film ''[[The Neon Demon]]'' (2016), followed by roles in the comedy ''[[Fist Fight]]'' (2017), the horror film ''[[The Strangers: Prey at Night]]'' (2018), and the animated comedy ''[[Toy Story 4]]'' (2019). She returned to television with starring roles on the crime drama series ''[[Tin Star (TV series)|Tin Star]]'' (2017\u2013present) and on the [[NBC]] comedy-crime series ''[[Good Girls (TV series)|Good Girls]]'' (2018\u2013present).\n\n==Early life==\nHendricks was born May 3, 1975, in [[Knoxville]], [[Tennessee]],<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[United Press International]]|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/05/03/Famous-birthdays-for-May-3-Christina-Hendricks-Pom-Klementieff/3081556672790/|title=Famous birthdays for May 3: Christina Hendricks, Pom Klementieff|author=UPI Staff|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505062603/https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/05/03/Famous-birthdays-for-May-3-Christina-Hendricks-Pom-Klementieff/3081556672790/|archive-date=May 5, 2019|date=May 3, 2019}}</ref> the second child of Jackie Sue Hendricks (n\u00e9e Raymond), a psychologist, and Robert Hendricks, a [[United States Forest Service|Forest Service]] employee originally from [[Birmingham]], [[England]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Christina Hendricks: a fine figure of a woman |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/4269856/Christina-Hendricks-a-fine-figure-of-a-woman.html|accessdate=September 14, 2012|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=January 19, 2009 |first=Catherine |last= Elsworth}}</ref> Through her father, she has dual British and American citizenship.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2011/sep/16/christina-hendricks-drive-mad-men?INTCMP=SRCH |title=Mad Men and me: Christina Hendricks interview |first=Hadley |last=Freeman|work=[[The Guardian]] |date=September 16, 2011|location=London |issn=0261-3077 |oclc=60623878 |accessdate=September 20, 2011}}</ref> Hendricks has one older brother.<ref name=tindia/> Though born in Tennessee, Hendricks's family relocated frequently due to her father's Forest Service job, first to [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] when she was two months old,{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=23:19}} and subsequently to [[Portland, Oregon]], where Hendricks attended elementary school.<ref name=tindia>{{cite web|work=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/entertainment/curveball-christina/cid/1437077|title=Curveball Christina|date=September 8, 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190331005341/https://www.telegraphindia.com/entertainment/curveball-christina/cid/1437077|archive-date=March 31, 2019|author=Bureau, T. T.|access-date=March 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=23:00}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movieweb.com/christina-hendricks-talks-all-star-superman/|work=MovieWeb|title=Christina Hendricks Talks All-Star Superman|date=March 2016|accessdate=November 5, 2016|author=Orange, Alan}}</ref>\n\nWhen she was nine years old, the family left Portland, relocating to [[Twin Falls, Idaho]], where Hendricks completed elementary and middle school.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=21:58\u201324:10}} Hendricks described her family as \"outdoorsy\", relating that she, her brother, and parents frequently went on camping trips in the [[Pacific Northwest]].{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=20:20}} Hendricks' mother encouraged her and her brother to join a local theater group in Twin Falls as a way of making friends, and Hendricks appeared in a production of ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]''.<ref name=tindia/> \"I had all these amazing friends through the theatre company,\u201d she recalled. \u201cAnd it was a community that really respected theatre. The kids would put on a play and the entire town would show. And you were cool if you were an actor.\u201d<ref name=tindia/> Hendricks, a natural blonde, began coloring her hair red at age 10, inspired by the book ''[[Anne of Green Gables]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/mad-men-star-christina-hendricks-reveals-shes-a-natural-blonde-not-a-red-head/news-story/55e2a1ce235d271d60f4247606c85d4f?sv=49b7e9f7e298274a7451dbe43f586473|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=Australia|title=Mad Men star Christina Hendricks reveals she's a natural blonde not a red-head|date=March 10, 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513025023/https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/mad-men-star-christina-hendricks-reveals-shes-a-natural-blonde-not-a-red-head/news-story/55e2a1ce235d271d60f4247606c85d4f?sv=49b7e9f7e298274a7451dbe43f586473|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhen Hendricks was a teenager, her father's job necessitated the family move near [[Washington, D.C.]], so the family settled in [[Fairfax, Virginia]]. Hendricks described the move from Idaho to Virginia as \"traumatic\" for her, and she was frequently bullied while attending [[Fairfax High School (Fairfax, Virginia)|Fairfax High School]].<ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=Kelly |date=September 23, 2014 |title=Christina Hendricks hated Fairfax High. Today's students say she wouldn't now. |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/christina-hendricks-hated-fairfax-high-todays-students-say-she-wouldnt-now/2014/09/22/8d41a79a-3dd0-11e4-b0ea-8141703bbf6f_story.html |accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> Hendricks described herself as an \"outcast\" and a \"[[goth subculture|goth]]\", and found companionship in the school's drama department, where she appeared in plays.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/9088143/Christina-Hendricks-I-was-bullied-at-school-for-being-a-goth.html|work=The Telegraph|title=Christina Hendricks: 'I was bullied at school for being a goth'|date=February 27, 2012|accessdate=November 5, 2016|author=Wardrop, Murray}}</ref> In addition to theater, Hendricks also studied [[ballet]] throughout her teenage years.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=40:57}} She left Fairfax High School during her senior year, and completed her studies at a local [[community college]].{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=42:24}}\n\n==Career==\n===1994\u20132006: Modeling career and early acting===\nAfter high school, Hendricks worked as a [[receptionist]] and shampoo girl at a salon before entering a competition to appear on the cover of ''[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]'' magazine. This resulted in her signing with a [[IMG (company)|IMG Models]],{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=48:00}} after which she moved to [[New York City]] at age 18,<ref>{{cite news |first=Elizabeth |last=Day |date=August 3, 2014 |title=Christina Hendricks: 'My agency dropped me when I first agreed to play Joan in Mad Men' |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2014/aug/03/christina-hendricks-joan-mad-men-gods-pocket-interview |accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> forgoing her pre-acceptance into [[Virginia Commonwealth University]]'s drama school.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=48:58}}\n\nHendricks began modeling in New York, [[London]], and [[Japan]] between the ages of 18 and 27 before transitioning into appearing in commercials.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=49:30\u201351:45}} Hendricks lived in London for around a year during this period, residing with two friends who were working there as teachers.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=52:40}} In her early twenties, Hendricks relocated with her mother and brother to [[Los Angeles]], California.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=53:00\u201354:00}} Initially, Hendricks pursued a career working in the administrative sector of the music business, but was dissuaded by friends, and instead continued working as a model before auditioning for acting roles.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=54:00}} She appeared in commercials for [[Carl's Jr.]] and [[Dr. Pepper]],{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=54:15}} and also starred in the music video for [[Everclear (band)|Everclear]]'s \"One Hit Wonder\" (1997).<ref>{{cite web|title='Best-Looking Woman' Christina Hendricks is a Music Video Star|url= http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/stop-the-presses/best-looking-woman-christina-hendricks-is-a-music-video-star.html|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date= June 2, 2010|accessdate=September 29, 2012}}</ref> She appeared as the hand model in the poster for the film ''[[American Beauty (1999 film)|American Beauty]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hendricks |first1=Christina |title=Christina Hendricks (@actuallychristinahendricks) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B1fFJFFlt95/ |website=Instagram |accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Christina Hendricks.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Hendricks in 2005]]\nShe made her television debut in the MTV anthology series ''[[Undressed]]''. Her first starring role was as an intern on ''[[Beggars and Choosers (TV series)|Beggars and Choosers]]'', a [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] comedy series focused on a group of young professionals. The series filmed in [[Vancouver]], and ran from 1999 to 2001.<ref name=qa>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2010/08/emmys-qa-with-supporting-drama-actress-nominee-christina-hendricks-60916/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|title=EMMYS: Q&A With Supporting Drama Actress Nominee Christina Hendricks|date=August 11, 2010|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513053832/https://deadline.com/2010/08/emmys-qa-with-supporting-drama-actress-nominee-christina-hendricks-60916/|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> During this time, she also had a guest role on the series ''[[Angel (1999 TV series)|Angel]]'' in 2000. Hendricks subsequently appeared in the television film ''The Big Time'' (2002), and had recurring guest roles on ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' (2002),  ''[[The Court (TV series)|The Court]]'' (2003), and ''[[Firefly (TV series)|Firefly]]'' (2002\u20132003).\n\nAfter a guest appearance on ''[[Tru Calling]]'', Hendricks was cast as Nicolette Ray in the legal drama ''[[Kevin Hill]]'', which ran between 2004 and 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/kevin-hill/cast/100240/|work=[[TV Guide]]|title=''Kevin Hill'' Cast and Crew|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513054603/https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/kevin-hill/cast/100240/|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132015: ''Mad Men''===\nShe played [[Joan Holloway]] on the AMC series ''[[Mad Men]]'' as the office manager of advertising agency Sterling Cooper & Partners, providing mentoring to a group of women who must deal with the come-ons and callousness of professional advertising executives. Her performance has received critical praise, resulting in six [[Primetime Emmys|Primetime Emmy]] nominations for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series over the course of its seven seasons.<ref name=emmy>\u00b0{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/bios/christina-hendricks|work=[[Primetime Emmys]]|publisher=Television Academy|title=Christina Hendricks|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513060617/https://www.emmys.com/bios/christina-hendricks|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2007, Hendricks made her feature film debut in ''[[La Cucina (film)|La Cucina]]'', a [[drama film]] that premiered on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] in December 2009, and which stars Hendricks as a writer.<ref name=cucina>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2009/12/10/move-over-julia-child-christina-hendricks-is-in-the-kitchen/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=December 10, 2009|title=Move over Julia Child, Christina Hendricks is in the kitchen!|author=Mitchell, Wendy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120112820/http://www.ew.com/article/2009/12/10/move-over-julia-child-christina-hendricks-is-in-the-kitchen|archive-date=November 20, 2015}}</ref> The same year, she starred in the thriller film ''[[South of Pico]]'',<ref name=pico>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2011/03/christina-hendricks-uses-mad-men-hiatus-for-seconds-of-pleasure-114167/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|title=Christina Hendricks Uses 'Mad Men' Hiatus For 'Seconds Of Pleasure'|author=Fleming, Mike Jr.|date=March 15, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223020932/http://deadline.com/2011/03/christina-hendricks-uses-mad-men-hiatus-for-seconds-of-pleasure-114167/|archive-date=December 23, 2017}}</ref> and appeared in four episodes of the [[NBC]] series ''[[Life (US TV series)|Life]]'' (2007\u20132008) in the recurring role of Olivia, detective [[Charlie Crews]]' soon-to-be stepmother and Ted Earley's love interest.\n\nOn October 11, 2009, Hendricks married actor [[Geoffrey Arend]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Christina Hendricks Marries in New York|first=Elaine|last=Aradillas|date=October 11, 2009|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20311577,00.html|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}</ref> In 2010, she appeared in the musical video for \"[[Broken Bells (album)|The Ghost Inside]]\" by [[Broken Bells]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Avalos |first=Steven |url= http://www.popeater.com/2010/06/02/christina-hendricks-broken-bells-music-video/ |title= Christina Hendricks Stars in Broken Bells Music Video |publisher=[[PopEater]] |date=June 2, 2010 |accessdate=March 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared in a supporting role in the action-thriller ''[[Drive (2011 film)|Drive]]'' (2011), directed by [[Nicolas Winding Refn]], alongside [[Carey Mulligan]] and [[Ryan Gosling]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Helyer |first=Rachel |url= http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/68437,people,news,mad-men-christina-hendricks-eyes-big-screen-roles-drive |title=Mad Men's Hendricks eyes big-screen roles |work=The First Post |date=September 9, 2010 |accessdate=June 3, 2013}}</ref> The following year, she was cast in a supporting role in [[Sally Potter]]'s drama film ''[[Ginger & Rosa]]'', playing the countercultural mother of a teenager growing up in the 1960s.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/15/movies/ginger-rosa-starring-elle-fanning-and-alice-englert.html|date=March 15, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104200241/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/15/movies/ginger-rosa-starring-elle-fanning-and-alice-englert.html|archive-date=November 4, 2017|title=Ticking Bomb in Their Friendship|author=Scott, A. O.}}</ref> In 2013, Hendricks appeared onstage in a production of [[Stephen Sondheim]]'s ''[[Company (musical)|Company]]'' at the [[Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts]] opposite [[Martha Plimpton]] and [[Stephen Colbert]].<ref name=co>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/11/08/243932076/stephen-colbert-in-good-company-on-broadway|work=[[National Public Radio]]|title=Stephen Colbert: In Good 'Company' On Broadway|date=November 8, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507200817/http://www.npr.org/2013/11/08/243932076/stephen-colbert-in-good-company-on-broadway|archive-date=May 7, 2017}}</ref> Hendricks also lent her voice and likeness in the 2011 racing video game ''[[Need for Speed: The Run]]'', playing the role of Sam Harper opposite [[Sean Faris]].<ref name=\"gabbygabbynfs\">{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Tom |title=Christina Hendricks in NFS: The Run |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-10-18-christina-hendricks-in-nfs-the-run |website=Eurogamer |accessdate=9 September 2019 |language=en |date=18 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Frannich\">{{cite web |last1=Frannich |first1=Darren |title=Christina Hendricks starring in 'Need for Speed: The Run' -- EXCLUSIVE |url=https://ew.com/article/2011/10/17/need-for-speed-christina-hendricks/ |website=EW.com |accessdate=9 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, she played the lead character in Gosling's directorial debut ''[[Lost River (film)|Lost River]]'', a fantasy film set in Detroit.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cannes 2014: The bafflement of Ryan Gosling's 'Lost River'|url=https://latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-cannes-2014-ryan-gosling-lost-river-20140521-story.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref> The film received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lost_river_2015/|title=''Lost River''|access-date=May 13, 2019}}</ref> The following year, she starred in the novel adaptation ''[[Dark Places (2015 film)|Dark Places]]'' (2015) opposite [[Charlize Theron]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dark Places|url=https://dreadcentral.com/news/91742/dark-places-international-one-sheet-laid/|publisher=Dread Central|accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref> After the conclusion of ''Mad Men'' in 2015, Hendricks starred as a prostitute in two seasons of the [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[Another Period]]'' (2015\u20132016), set during the early 20th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/another-period-canceled-3-seasons-comedy-central/|work=The Wrap|title='Another Period' Canceled by Comedy Central After 3 Seasons|last=Maas|first=Jennifer|date=November 29, 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513062524/https://www.thewrap.com/another-period-canceled-3-seasons-comedy-central/|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u2013present: Subsequent acting roles===\nIn 2016, she appeared as one of the leads in Refn's thriller film ''[[The Neon Demon]]'', portraying a modeling agent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Keanu Reeves, Christina Hendricks Join Refn's 'The Neon Demon'|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3331132/keanu-reeves-christina-hendricks-join-refns-neon-demon/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref> Critical response to the film was polarized, though the French film magazine ''[[Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma]]'' named it the third-best film of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|work=Cahiers du cinema|url= https://www.cahiersducinema.com/produit/decembre-2016-n728 |title=  Top Ten 2016, D\u00e9cembre 2016 n\u00b0728 }}</ref> The same year, she starred in six episodes of the series ''[[Hap and Leonard]]'', playing the ex-wife of investigator Hap Collins.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url=https://ew.com/article/2016/03/31/christina-hendricks-hap-leonard/|title=Christina Hendricks on Hap and Leonard nailed hand scene|last=Collis|first=Clark|date=March 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811141533/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/03/31/christina-hendricks-hap-leonard|archive-date=August 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she was seen in home-invasion based horror film ''[[The Strangers: Prey at Night]],'' playing the matriarch of a family under siege by killers. Upon release, the film received generally unfavorable reviews from critics,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.avclub.com/the-sequel-prey-at-night-slashes-the-strangers-home-in-1823584222|title=The sequel Prey At Night slashes The Strangers' home-invasion premise into... art?|last=Vishnevetsky|first=Ignatiy|work=The A.V. Club|access-date=2018-03-10|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2018/03/09/strangers-prey-night-review/|title=Review \u2013 Strangers: Prey at Night is Why Some Films Don't Need Sequels|date=March 9, 2018|work=Bleeding Cool News And Rumors|access-date=March 10, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/the-strangers-prey-at-night-review-1202720596/|title=Film Review: 'The Strangers: Prey at Night'|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|date=March 8, 2018|work=Variety|access-date=March 20, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> though ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Benjamin Lee praised Hendricks' performance.<ref name=guardian>{{cite web|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Lee |first=Benjamin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/mar/08/the-strangers-prey-at-night-review-slick-sequel-fails-to-replicate-scares|title=The Strangers: Prey at Night review \u2013 slick sequel fails to replicate scares|accessdate=March 8, 2018|date=March 8, 2018}} {{rating|2|5}}</ref> It was a commercial success, however, grossing $30 million.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|title=The Strangers: Prey at Night (2018) |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Strangers-Prey-at-Night-The#tab=summary|accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Hendricks returned to television in the [[Amazon Prime]] series ''[[The Romanoffs]]'', reuniting with ''Mad Men'' creator [[Matthew Weiner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.avclub.com/the-romanoffs-tells-a-frightening-story-of-ghosts-and-u-1829857135|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|title=The Romanoffs tells a frightening story of ghosts and unprofessional work environment|last=Wanserki|first=Nick|date=October 19, 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513075435/https://tv.avclub.com/the-romanoffs-tells-a-frightening-story-of-ghosts-and-u-1829857135|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She was cast as one of the leads on the [[NBC]] comedy crime series ''[[Good Girls (TV series)|Good Girls]]'', playing a woman who attempts to gain financial control of her life by holding up a grocery store.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[United Press International]]|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2019/03/03/Co-stars-of-Good-Girls-Fans-love-flawed-but-believable-friends/6851551547021/|title=Co-stars of 'Good Girls': Fans love flawed, but believable friends|last=Butler|first=Karen|date=March 4, 2019|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513075605/https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2019/03/03/Co-stars-of-Good-Girls-Fans-love-flawed-but-believable-friends/6851551547021/|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The show was renewed for a third season in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title='Good Girls' Renewed For Season 3 By NBC |url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/good-girls-renewed-season-3-nbc-1202594899/ |website=Deadline}}</ref> In late 2018, Hendricks starred opposite [[Sienna Miller]] in the drama ''[[American Woman (2018 film)|American Woman]]'', portraying a woman helping her sister raise her family in rural Pennsylvania.<ref name=am>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/trailers/2019/05/06/american-woman-trailer-sienna-miller/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|title=American Woman trailer glimpses a career-high performance from Sienna Miller|last=Romano|first=Nick|date=May 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506204314/https://ew.com/trailers/2019/05/06/american-woman-trailer-sienna-miller/|archive-date=May 6, 2019}}</ref> She also supplied the voice of [[List of Toy Story characters#Gabby Gabby|Gabby Gabby]], the main [[Sympathetic villain|antivillain]] in the [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]]/[[Pixar]] animated sequel ''[[Toy Story 4]]'' (2019).<ref name=toy>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/03/28/toy-story-4-christina-hendricks/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|title=Meet Christina Hendricks' 'cold, terrifying' Toy Story 4 villain|last=Snetiker|first=Marc|date=March 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328191654/https://ew.com/movies/2019/03/28/toy-story-4-christina-hendricks/|archive-date=March 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, it was announced that Hendricks and husband [[Geoffrey Arend]] had separated after 10 years of marriage.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/christina-hendricks-geoffrey-arend-split-10-year-marriage-1248683|title=Christina Hendricks and Geoffrey Arend Split After 10 Years of Marriage|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Schaffstall|first=Katherine|date=18 October 2019|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Public image ==\n[[File:Christina Hendricks 3, 2012.jpg|thumb|Christina Hendricks launches a Spectacle Wearer of the Year competition at The Star in Sydney, Australia, 2012.]]\nHendricks has been credited as having an ideal shape for a woman by British Equalities Minister [[Lynne Featherstone]] who praised Hendricks' [[female body shape|hourglass figure]], saying \"Christina Hendricks is absolutely fabulous... We need more of these role models. There is such a sensation when there is a curvy role model. It shouldn't be so unusual.\"<ref name=\"BBCjuly27\">{{cite news|title=Does Christina Hendricks have a body women should aspire to|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-10760903|newspaper=BBC News Magazine|accessdate=May 28, 2011|date=July 27, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' television critic Mary McNamara says her portrayal of Joan has revolutionized perceptions of beauty on television.<ref>{{cite news |last= Geoghegan |first= Tom |title= Does Christina Hendricks have a body women should aspire to? |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-10760903 |accessdate=May 28, 2011|newspaper=BBC News Magazine|date=July 27, 2010}}</ref> She has been called the \"new modern ideal of Hollywood glamour\u2014full figured, voluptuous; a throwback to the days of [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Jane Russell]] and [[Veronica Lake]]\".<ref>{{cite web |last= Kiley |first= David |title= Mad Men Star Christina Hendricks The New Face of Vivienne Westwood |url= http://www.luxist.com/2011/03/02/mad-men-star-christina-hendricks-the-new-face-of-vivienne-westwo/ |publisher= luxist.com |accessdate= May 28, 2011 |date= March 2, 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110506132019/http://www.luxist.com/2011/03/02/mad-men-star-christina-hendricks-the-new-face-of-vivienne-westwo/ |archive-date= May 6, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> British designer [[Vivienne Westwood]] selected Hendricks to represent her \"Get A Life\" Palladium jewelry collection in March 2011.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nA study by the British Association of Aesthetic [[Plastic surgery|Plastic Surgeons]] attributed a 10% rise in 2010 of the number of British women receiving [[breast augmentation]] surgery in part to Hendricks' influence.<ref name=lusher20110130>{{cite news|last=Lusher|first=Adam|title=Mad Men star Christina Hendricks sparks rush for breast implants|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/8290407/Mad-Men-star-Christina-Hendricks-sparks-rush-for-breast-implants.html |accessdate=January 31, 2011|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=January 30, 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nHendricks has moved away from accepting the term \"full-figured\" and once lambasted a reporter who used the term while interviewing her.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hollywood's voluptuous beauty was offended? Go (full) figure \u2026 |url= http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/fashion/hollywoods-voluptuous-beauty-was-offended-go-full-figure-8230-20121013-27jp5.html |accessdate=October 14, 2012|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=October 14, 2012|location=Sydney}}</ref> Hendricks commented in September 2010 that the media is too focused on women's bodies and not their actual talents.  \"I was working my butt off on the show [''Mad Men''] and then all anyone was talking about was my body.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Hunter |first= Aina |title= Christina Hendricks' Measurements: Naked \"I Look Like a Woman\"|url= http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-504763_162-20009422-10391704.html |accessdate= May 28, 2011 |date= July 2010 |publisher= CBS News }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://showbiz.sky.com/christinas-body-rant | title= Christina's body comments | publisher= Sky Showbiz | url-status=dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100905175036/http://showbiz.sky.com/christinas-body-rant | archivedate= September 5, 2010 | df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Christina Hendricks on screen and stage}}\n\n== Accolades ==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Christina Hendricks}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite av media|last1=Maron|first1=Marc|author1-link=Marc Maron|last2=Hendricks|first2=Christina|date=April 15, 2019|title=Episode 1010|work=[[WTF with Marc Maron]]|ref=harv|url=http://www.wtfpod.com/podcast/episode-1010-christina-hendricks}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Christina Hendricks}}\n* {{IMDb name|376716|Christina Hendricks}}\n* {{AllRovi person|329699|title=Christina Hendricks}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Christina Hendricks|Awards for Christina Hendricks]]\n|list  = \n{{Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Drama Supporting Actress}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwardsTVEnsembleDrama}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hendricks, Christina}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Idaho]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Actresses of British descent]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actors from Fairfax, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:People from Knoxville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:People from Twin Falls, Idaho]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Christina Hendricks\n| image              = Christina Hendricks at PaleyFest 2014.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Hendricks at the 2014 [[Paley Center for Media|PaleyFest]] for ''[[Mad Men]]''\n| birth_name         = Christina Rene Hendricks\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1975|05|03}}\n| birth_place        = [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]], [[Tennessee]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actress|model}}\n| years_active       = 1999\u2013present\n| height             = {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/christina-hendricks-measurements-too-big-for-hollywood/|work=[[CBS News]]|title=Christina Hendricks' Measurements - Too Big for Hollywood?|last=Hunter|first=Aina|date=September 21, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217202329/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/christina-hendricks-measurements-too-big-for-hollywood/|archive-date=December 17, 2013}}</ref>\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Geoffrey Arend]]|2009|2019|reason={{abbr|sep.|separated}}}}\n| home_town          = [[Twin Falls, Idaho]], U.S.\n}}\n\n'''Christina Rene Hendricks''' (born May 3, 1975)<ref>{{cite web|title=About Christina Hendricks|url=https://www.vogue.in/topics/christina-hendricks|work=[[Vogue India]]|accessdate= July 5, 2018}}</ref> is an American actress and former model. Her accolades include six [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations, two [[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s, and two [[Critics' Choice Television Award|Critics' Choice Awards]] for [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Drama Series|Best Supporting Actress in a Drama Series]]. A 2010 poll of female readers taken by ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' magazine named her \"the sexiest woman in the world,\"<ref name=\"esquireApril20\" /> and voted as Best Looking Woman in America the same year.<ref name=\"esquireApril20\">{{cite web |title= The Esquire Survey of the American Woman |url= http://www.esquire.com/women/women-issue/survey-of-american-women-0510/ |work= Esquire|date= April 20, 2010 |accessdate= May 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Welles |first= Denmark |url= http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/62338,people,entertainment,christina-hendricks-voted-best-looking-woman-in-us-esquire-mad-men |title= Mad Men's Christina Hendricks voted best-looking woman in US &#124; People |work=The First Post |date=April 23, 2010 |accessdate=February 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBorn in Tennessee, Hendricks was raised in [[Portland, Oregon]] and [[Twin Falls, Idaho]], where she became active in local theater. After completing high school in [[Virginia]], Hendricks relocated to New York City and pursued a career as a model following her entry into a ''[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]'' cover contest. She continued to work internationally as a model for over a decade before transitioning into acting.\n\nHendricks had recurring roles in several television series, including ''[[Beggars and Choosers (TV series)|Beggars and Choosers]]'' (2001\u20132002) and ''[[Kevin Hill]]'' (2004\u20132005) before being cast as [[Joan Holloway]] on the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] period drama series ''[[Mad Men]]'' in 2007, of which she remained a main cast member until the series' conclusion in 2015. She received critical acclaim for her role on the series, including six Emmy Award nominations and multiple Screen Actors Guild Awards for Best Ensemble. While starring on ''Mad Men'', Hendricks also began appearing in films, receiving critical notice for her performance in [[Nicolas Winding Refn]]'s thriller ''[[Drive (2011 film)|Drive]]'' (2011), [[Sally Potter]]'s drama ''[[Ginger & Rosa]]'' (2012), and [[Ryan Gosling]]'s neo-noir fantasy ''[[Lost River (film)|Lost River]]'' (2014).\n\nFollowing the conclusion of ''Mad Men'', Hendricks starred in the comedy series ''[[Another Period]]'' from 2015 to 2016, and in the [[SundanceTV]] drama series ''[[Hap and Leonard (TV series)|Hap and Leonard]]'' (2016). She reunited with Refn for a supporting role in his thriller film ''[[The Neon Demon]]'' (2016), followed by roles in the comedy ''[[Fist Fight]]'' (2017), the horror film ''[[The Strangers: Prey at Night]]'' (2018), and the animated comedy ''[[Toy Story 4]]'' (2019). She returned to television with starring roles on the crime drama series ''[[Tin Star (TV series)|Tin Star]]'' (2017\u2013present) and on the [[NBC]] comedy-crime series ''[[Good Girls (TV series)|Good Girls]]'' (2018\u2013present).\n\n==Early life==\nHendricks was born May 3, 1975, in [[Knoxville]], [[Tennessee]],<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[United Press International]]|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/05/03/Famous-birthdays-for-May-3-Christina-Hendricks-Pom-Klementieff/3081556672790/|title=Famous birthdays for May 3: Christina Hendricks, Pom Klementieff|author=UPI Staff|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505062603/https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/05/03/Famous-birthdays-for-May-3-Christina-Hendricks-Pom-Klementieff/3081556672790/|archive-date=May 5, 2019|date=May 3, 2019}}</ref> the second child of Jackie Sue Hendricks (n\u00e9e Raymond), a psychologist, and Robert Hendricks, a [[United States Forest Service|Forest Service]] employee originally from [[Birmingham]], [[England]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Christina Hendricks: a fine figure of a woman |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/4269856/Christina-Hendricks-a-fine-figure-of-a-woman.html|accessdate=September 14, 2012|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=January 19, 2009 |first=Catherine |last= Elsworth}}</ref> Through her father, she has dual British and American citizenship.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2011/sep/16/christina-hendricks-drive-mad-men?INTCMP=SRCH |title=Mad Men and me: Christina Hendricks interview |first=Hadley |last=Freeman|work=[[The Guardian]] |date=September 16, 2011|location=London |issn=0261-3077 |oclc=60623878 |accessdate=September 20, 2011}}</ref> Hendricks has one older brother.<ref name=tindia/> Though born in Tennessee, Hendricks's family relocated frequently due to her father's Forest Service job, first to [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] when she was two months old,{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=23:19}} and subsequently to [[Portland, Oregon]], where Hendricks attended elementary school.<ref name=tindia>{{cite web|work=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/entertainment/curveball-christina/cid/1437077|title=Curveball Christina|date=September 8, 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190331005341/https://www.telegraphindia.com/entertainment/curveball-christina/cid/1437077|archive-date=March 31, 2019|author=Bureau, T. T.|access-date=March 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=23:00}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movieweb.com/christina-hendricks-talks-all-star-superman/|work=MovieWeb|title=Christina Hendricks Talks All-Star Superman|date=March 2016|accessdate=November 5, 2016|author=Orange, Alan}}</ref>\n\nWhen she was nine years old, the family left Portland, relocating to [[Twin Falls, Idaho]], where Hendricks completed elementary and middle school.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=21:58\u201324:10}} Hendricks described her family as \"outdoorsy\", relating that she, her brother, and parents frequently went on camping trips in the [[Pacific Northwest]].{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=20:20}} Hendricks' mother encouraged her and her brother to join a local theater group in Twin Falls as a way of making friends, and Hendricks appeared in a production of ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]''.<ref name=tindia/> \"I had all these amazing friends through the theatre company,\u201d she recalled. \u201cAnd it was a community that really respected theatre. The kids would put on a play and the entire town would show. And you were cool if you were an actor.\u201d<ref name=tindia/> Hendricks, a natural blonde, began coloring her hair red at age 10, inspired by the book ''[[Anne of Green Gables]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/mad-men-star-christina-hendricks-reveals-shes-a-natural-blonde-not-a-red-head/news-story/55e2a1ce235d271d60f4247606c85d4f?sv=49b7e9f7e298274a7451dbe43f586473|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=Australia|title=Mad Men star Christina Hendricks reveals she's a natural blonde not a red-head|date=March 10, 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513025023/https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/mad-men-star-christina-hendricks-reveals-shes-a-natural-blonde-not-a-red-head/news-story/55e2a1ce235d271d60f4247606c85d4f?sv=49b7e9f7e298274a7451dbe43f586473|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhen Hendricks was a teenager, her father's job necessitated the family move near [[Washington, D.C.]], so the family settled in [[Fairfax, Virginia]]. Hendricks described the move from Idaho to Virginia as \"traumatic\" for her, and she was frequently bullied while attending [[Fairfax High School (Fairfax, Virginia)|Fairfax High School]].<ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=Kelly |date=September 23, 2014 |title=Christina Hendricks hated Fairfax High. Today's students say she wouldn't now. |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/christina-hendricks-hated-fairfax-high-todays-students-say-she-wouldnt-now/2014/09/22/8d41a79a-3dd0-11e4-b0ea-8141703bbf6f_story.html |accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> Hendricks described herself as an \"outcast\" and a \"[[goth subculture|goth]],\" and found companionship in the school's drama department, where she appeared in plays.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/9088143/Christina-Hendricks-I-was-bullied-at-school-for-being-a-goth.html|work=The Telegraph|title=Christina Hendricks: 'I was bullied at school for being a goth'|date=February 27, 2012|accessdate=November 5, 2016|author=Wardrop, Murray}}</ref> In addition to theater, Hendricks also studied [[ballet]] throughout her teenage years.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=40:57}} She left Fairfax High School during her senior year, and completed her studies at a local [[community college]].{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=42:24}}\n\n==Career==\n===1994\u20132006: Modeling career and early acting===\nAfter high school, Hendricks worked as a [[receptionist]] and shampoo girl at a salon before entering a competition to appear on the cover of ''[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]'' magazine. This resulted in her signing with a [[IMG (company)|IMG Models]],{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=48:00}} after which she moved to [[New York City]] at age 18,<ref>{{cite news |first=Elizabeth |last=Day |date=August 3, 2014 |title=Christina Hendricks: 'My agency dropped me when I first agreed to play Joan in Mad Men' |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2014/aug/03/christina-hendricks-joan-mad-men-gods-pocket-interview |accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> forgoing her pre-acceptance into [[Virginia Commonwealth University]]'s drama school.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=48:58}}\n\nHendricks began modeling in New York, [[London]], and [[Japan]] between the ages of 18 and 27 before transitioning into appearing in commercials.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=49:30\u201351:45}} Hendricks lived in London for around a year during this period, residing with two friends who were working there as teachers.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=52:40}} In her early twenties, Hendricks relocated with her mother and brother to [[Los Angeles]], California.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=53:00\u201354:00}} Initially, Hendricks pursued a career working in the administrative sector of the music business, but was dissuaded by friends, and instead continued working as a model before auditioning for acting roles.{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=54:00}} She appeared in commercials for [[Carl's Jr.]] and [[Dr. Pepper]],{{sfn|Maron|Hendricks|2019|loc=54:15}} and also starred in the music video for [[Everclear (band)|Everclear]]'s \"One Hit Wonder\" (1997).<ref>{{cite web|title='Best-Looking Woman' Christina Hendricks is a Music Video Star|url= http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/stop-the-presses/best-looking-woman-christina-hendricks-is-a-music-video-star.html|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date= June 2, 2010|accessdate=September 29, 2012}}</ref> She appeared as the hand model in the poster for the film ''[[American Beauty (1999 film)|American Beauty]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hendricks |first1=Christina |title=Christina Hendricks (@actuallychristinahendricks) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B1fFJFFlt95/ |website=Instagram |accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Christina Hendricks.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Hendricks in 2005]]\nShe made her television debut in the MTV anthology series ''[[Undressed]]''. Her first starring role was as an intern on ''[[Beggars and Choosers (TV series)|Beggars and Choosers]]'', a [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] comedy series focused on a group of young professionals. The series filmed in [[Vancouver]], and ran from 1999 to 2001.<ref name=qa>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2010/08/emmys-qa-with-supporting-drama-actress-nominee-christina-hendricks-60916/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|title=EMMYS: Q&A With Supporting Drama Actress Nominee Christina Hendricks|date=August 11, 2010|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513053832/https://deadline.com/2010/08/emmys-qa-with-supporting-drama-actress-nominee-christina-hendricks-60916/|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> During this time, she also had a guest role on the series ''[[Angel (1999 TV series)|Angel]]'' in 2000. Hendricks subsequently appeared in the television film ''The Big Time'' (2002), and had recurring guest roles on ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' (2002),  ''[[The Court (TV series)|The Court]]'' (2003), and ''[[Firefly (TV series)|Firefly]]'' (2002\u20132003).\n\nAfter a guest appearance on ''[[Tru Calling]]'', Hendricks was cast as Nicolette Ray in the legal drama ''[[Kevin Hill]]'', which ran between 2004 and 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/kevin-hill/cast/100240/|work=[[TV Guide]]|title=''Kevin Hill'' Cast and Crew|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513054603/https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/kevin-hill/cast/100240/|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132015: ''Mad Men''===\nShe played [[Joan Holloway]] on the AMC series ''[[Mad Men]]'' as the office manager of advertising agency Sterling Cooper & Partners, providing mentoring to a group of women who must deal with the come-ons and callousness of professional advertising executives. Her performance has received critical praise, resulting in six [[Primetime Emmys|Primetime Emmy]] nominations for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series over the course of its seven seasons.<ref name=emmy>\u00b0{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/bios/christina-hendricks|work=[[Primetime Emmys]]|publisher=Television Academy|title=Christina Hendricks|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513060617/https://www.emmys.com/bios/christina-hendricks|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2007, Hendricks made her feature film debut in ''[[La Cucina (film)|La Cucina]]'', a [[drama film]] that premiered on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] in December 2009, and which stars Hendricks as a writer.<ref name=cucina>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2009/12/10/move-over-julia-child-christina-hendricks-is-in-the-kitchen/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=December 10, 2009|title=Move over Julia Child, Christina Hendricks is in the kitchen!|author=Mitchell, Wendy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120112820/http://www.ew.com/article/2009/12/10/move-over-julia-child-christina-hendricks-is-in-the-kitchen|archive-date=November 20, 2015}}</ref> The same year, she starred in the thriller film ''[[South of Pico]]'',<ref name=pico>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2011/03/christina-hendricks-uses-mad-men-hiatus-for-seconds-of-pleasure-114167/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|title=Christina Hendricks Uses 'Mad Men' Hiatus For 'Seconds Of Pleasure'|author=Fleming, Mike Jr.|date=March 15, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223020932/http://deadline.com/2011/03/christina-hendricks-uses-mad-men-hiatus-for-seconds-of-pleasure-114167/|archive-date=December 23, 2017}}</ref> and appeared in four episodes of the [[NBC]] series ''[[Life (US TV series)|Life]]'' (2007\u20132008) in the recurring role of Olivia, detective [[Charlie Crews]]' soon-to-be stepmother and Ted Earley's love interest.\n\nOn October 11, 2009, Hendricks married actor [[Geoffrey Arend]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Christina Hendricks Marries in New York|first=Elaine|last=Aradillas|date=October 11, 2009|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20311577,00.html|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}</ref> In 2010, she appeared in the musical video for \"[[Broken Bells (album)|The Ghost Inside]]\" by [[Broken Bells]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Avalos |first=Steven |url= http://www.popeater.com/2010/06/02/christina-hendricks-broken-bells-music-video/ |title= Christina Hendricks Stars in Broken Bells Music Video |publisher=[[PopEater]] |date=June 2, 2010 |accessdate=March 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared in a supporting role in the action-thriller ''[[Drive (2011 film)|Drive]]'' (2011), directed by [[Nicolas Winding Refn]], alongside [[Carey Mulligan]] and [[Ryan Gosling]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Helyer |first=Rachel |url= http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/68437,people,news,mad-men-christina-hendricks-eyes-big-screen-roles-drive |title=Mad Men's Hendricks eyes big-screen roles |work=The First Post |date=September 9, 2010 |accessdate=June 3, 2013}}</ref> The following year, she was cast in a supporting role in [[Sally Potter]]'s drama film ''[[Ginger & Rosa]]'', playing the countercultural mother of a teenager growing up in the 1960s.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/15/movies/ginger-rosa-starring-elle-fanning-and-alice-englert.html|date=March 15, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104200241/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/15/movies/ginger-rosa-starring-elle-fanning-and-alice-englert.html|archive-date=November 4, 2017|title=Ticking Bomb in Their Friendship|author=Scott, A. O.}}</ref> In 2013, Hendricks appeared onstage in a production of [[Stephen Sondheim]]'s ''[[Company (musical)|Company]]'' at the [[Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts]] opposite [[Martha Plimpton]] and [[Stephen Colbert]].<ref name=co>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/11/08/243932076/stephen-colbert-in-good-company-on-broadway|work=[[National Public Radio]]|title=Stephen Colbert: In Good 'Company' On Broadway|date=November 8, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507200817/http://www.npr.org/2013/11/08/243932076/stephen-colbert-in-good-company-on-broadway|archive-date=May 7, 2017}}</ref> Hendricks also lent her voice and likeness in the 2011 racing video game ''[[Need for Speed: The Run]]'', playing the role of Sam Harper opposite [[Sean Faris]].<ref name=\"gabbygabbynfs\">{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Tom |title=Christina Hendricks in NFS: The Run |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-10-18-christina-hendricks-in-nfs-the-run |website=Eurogamer |accessdate=9 September 2019 |language=en |date=18 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Frannich\">{{cite web |last1=Frannich |first1=Darren |title=Christina Hendricks starring in 'Need for Speed: The Run' -- EXCLUSIVE |url=https://ew.com/article/2011/10/17/need-for-speed-christina-hendricks/ |website=EW.com |accessdate=9 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, she played the lead character in Gosling's directorial debut ''[[Lost River (film)|Lost River]]'', a fantasy film set in Detroit.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cannes 2014: The bafflement of Ryan Gosling's 'Lost River'|url=https://latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-cannes-2014-ryan-gosling-lost-river-20140521-story.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref> The film received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lost_river_2015/|title=''Lost River''|access-date=May 13, 2019}}</ref> The following year, she starred in the novel adaptation ''[[Dark Places (2015 film)|Dark Places]]'' (2015) opposite [[Charlize Theron]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dark Places|url=https://dreadcentral.com/news/91742/dark-places-international-one-sheet-laid/|publisher=Dread Central|accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref> After the conclusion of ''Mad Men'' in 2015, Hendricks starred as a prostitute in two seasons of the [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[Another Period]]'' (2015\u20132016), set during the early 20th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/another-period-canceled-3-seasons-comedy-central/|work=The Wrap|title='Another Period' Canceled by Comedy Central After 3 Seasons|last=Maas|first=Jennifer|date=November 29, 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513062524/https://www.thewrap.com/another-period-canceled-3-seasons-comedy-central/|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u2013present: Subsequent acting roles===\nIn 2016, she appeared as one of the leads in Refn's thriller film ''[[The Neon Demon]]'', portraying a modeling agent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Keanu Reeves, Christina Hendricks Join Refn's 'The Neon Demon'|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3331132/keanu-reeves-christina-hendricks-join-refns-neon-demon/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref> Critical response to the film was polarized, though the French film magazine ''[[Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma]]'' named it the third-best film of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|work=Cahiers du cinema|url= https://www.cahiersducinema.com/produit/decembre-2016-n728 |title=  Top Ten 2016, D\u00e9cembre 2016 n\u00b0728 }}</ref> The same year, she starred in six episodes of the series ''[[Hap and Leonard]]'', playing the ex-wife of investigator Hap Collins.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url=https://ew.com/article/2016/03/31/christina-hendricks-hap-leonard/|title=Christina Hendricks on Hap and Leonard nailed hand scene|last=Collis|first=Clark|date=March 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811141533/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/03/31/christina-hendricks-hap-leonard|archive-date=August 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she was seen in home-invasion based horror film ''[[The Strangers: Prey at Night]],'' playing the matriarch of a family under siege by killers. Upon release, the film received generally unfavorable reviews from critics,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.avclub.com/the-sequel-prey-at-night-slashes-the-strangers-home-in-1823584222|title=The sequel Prey At Night slashes The Strangers' home-invasion premise into... art?|last=Vishnevetsky|first=Ignatiy|work=The A.V. Club|access-date=2018-03-10|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2018/03/09/strangers-prey-night-review/|title=Review \u2013 Strangers: Prey at Night is Why Some Films Don't Need Sequels|date=March 9, 2018|work=Bleeding Cool News And Rumors|access-date=March 10, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/the-strangers-prey-at-night-review-1202720596/|title=Film Review: 'The Strangers: Prey at Night'|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|date=March 8, 2018|work=Variety|access-date=March 20, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> though ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Benjamin Lee praised Hendricks' performance.<ref name=guardian>{{cite web|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Lee |first=Benjamin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/mar/08/the-strangers-prey-at-night-review-slick-sequel-fails-to-replicate-scares|title=The Strangers: Prey at Night review \u2013 slick sequel fails to replicate scares|accessdate=March 8, 2018|date=March 8, 2018}} {{rating|2|5}}</ref> It was a commercial success, however, grossing $30 million.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|title=The Strangers: Prey at Night (2018) |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Strangers-Prey-at-Night-The#tab=summary|accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Hendricks returned to television in the [[Amazon Prime]] series ''[[The Romanoffs]]'', reuniting with ''Mad Men'' creator [[Matthew Weiner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.avclub.com/the-romanoffs-tells-a-frightening-story-of-ghosts-and-u-1829857135|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|title=The Romanoffs tells a frightening story of ghosts and unprofessional work environment|last=Wanserki|first=Nick|date=October 19, 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513075435/https://tv.avclub.com/the-romanoffs-tells-a-frightening-story-of-ghosts-and-u-1829857135|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She was cast as one of the leads on the [[NBC]] comedy crime series ''[[Good Girls (TV series)|Good Girls]]'', playing a woman who attempts to gain financial control of her life by holding up a grocery store.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[United Press International]]|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2019/03/03/Co-stars-of-Good-Girls-Fans-love-flawed-but-believable-friends/6851551547021/|title=Co-stars of 'Good Girls': Fans love flawed, but believable friends|last=Butler|first=Karen|date=March 4, 2019|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190513075605/https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2019/03/03/Co-stars-of-Good-Girls-Fans-love-flawed-but-believable-friends/6851551547021/|archive-date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The show was renewed for a third season in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title='Good Girls' Renewed For Season 3 By NBC |url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/good-girls-renewed-season-3-nbc-1202594899/ |website=Deadline}}</ref> In late 2018, Hendricks starred opposite [[Sienna Miller]] in the drama ''[[American Woman (2018 film)|American Woman]]'', portraying a woman helping her sister raise her family in rural Pennsylvania.<ref name=am>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/trailers/2019/05/06/american-woman-trailer-sienna-miller/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|title=American Woman trailer glimpses a career-high performance from Sienna Miller|last=Romano|first=Nick|date=May 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506204314/https://ew.com/trailers/2019/05/06/american-woman-trailer-sienna-miller/|archive-date=May 6, 2019}}</ref> She also supplied the voice of [[List of Toy Story characters#Gabby Gabby|Gabby Gabby]], the main [[Sympathetic villain|antivillain]] in the [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]]/[[Pixar]] animated sequel ''[[Toy Story 4]]'' (2019).<ref name=toy>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/03/28/toy-story-4-christina-hendricks/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|title=Meet Christina Hendricks' 'cold, terrifying' Toy Story 4 villain|last=Snetiker|first=Marc|date=March 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328191654/https://ew.com/movies/2019/03/28/toy-story-4-christina-hendricks/|archive-date=March 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, it was announced that Hendricks and husband [[Geoffrey Arend]] had separated after 10 years of marriage.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/christina-hendricks-geoffrey-arend-split-10-year-marriage-1248683|title=Christina Hendricks and Geoffrey Arend Split After 10 Years of Marriage|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Schaffstall|first=Katherine|date=18 October 2019|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Public image ==\n[[File:Christina Hendricks 3, 2012.jpg|thumb|Christina Hendricks launches a Spectacle Wearer of the Year competition at The Star in Sydney, Australia, 2012.]]\nHendricks has been credited as having an ideal shape for a woman by British Equalities Minister [[Lynne Featherstone]] who praised Hendricks' [[female body shape|hourglass figure]], saying \"Christina Hendricks is absolutely fabulous... We need more of these role models. There is such a sensation when there is a curvy role model. It shouldn't be so unusual.\"<ref name=\"BBCjuly27\">{{cite news|title=Does Christina Hendricks have a body women should aspire to|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-10760903|newspaper=BBC News Magazine|accessdate=May 28, 2011|date=July 27, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' television critic Mary McNamara says her portrayal of Joan has revolutionized perceptions of beauty on television.<ref>{{cite news |last= Geoghegan |first= Tom |title= Does Christina Hendricks have a body women should aspire to? |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-10760903 |accessdate=May 28, 2011|newspaper=BBC News Magazine|date=July 27, 2010}}</ref> She has been called the \"new modern ideal of Hollywood glamour\u2014full figured, voluptuous; a throwback to the days of [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Jane Russell]] and [[Veronica Lake]]\".<ref>{{cite web |last= Kiley |first= David |title= Mad Men Star Christina Hendricks The New Face of Vivienne Westwood |url= http://www.luxist.com/2011/03/02/mad-men-star-christina-hendricks-the-new-face-of-vivienne-westwo/ |publisher= luxist.com |accessdate= May 28, 2011 |date= March 2, 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110506132019/http://www.luxist.com/2011/03/02/mad-men-star-christina-hendricks-the-new-face-of-vivienne-westwo/ |archive-date= May 6, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> British designer [[Vivienne Westwood]] selected Hendricks to represent her \"Get A Life\" Palladium jewelry collection in March 2011.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nA study by the British Association of Aesthetic [[Plastic surgery|Plastic Surgeons]] attributed a 10% rise in 2010 of the number of British women receiving [[breast augmentation]] surgery in part to Hendricks' influence.<ref name=lusher20110130>{{cite news|last=Lusher|first=Adam|title=Mad Men star Christina Hendricks sparks rush for breast implants|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/8290407/Mad-Men-star-Christina-Hendricks-sparks-rush-for-breast-implants.html |accessdate=January 31, 2011|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=January 30, 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nHendricks has moved away from accepting the term \"full-figured\" and once lambasted a reporter who used the term while interviewing her.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hollywood's voluptuous beauty was offended? Go (full) figure \u2026 |url= http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/fashion/hollywoods-voluptuous-beauty-was-offended-go-full-figure-8230-20121013-27jp5.html |accessdate=October 14, 2012|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=October 14, 2012|location=Sydney}}</ref> Hendricks commented in September 2010 that the media is too focused on women's bodies and not their actual talents.  \"I was working my butt off on the show [''Mad Men''] and then all anyone was talking about was my body.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Hunter |first= Aina |title= Christina Hendricks' Measurements: Naked \"I Look Like a Woman\"|url= http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-504763_162-20009422-10391704.html |accessdate= May 28, 2011 |date= July 2010 |publisher= CBS News }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://showbiz.sky.com/christinas-body-rant | title= Christina's body comments | publisher= Sky Showbiz | url-status=dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100905175036/http://showbiz.sky.com/christinas-body-rant | archivedate= September 5, 2010 | df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Christina Hendricks on screen and stage}}\n\n== Accolades ==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Christina Hendricks}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite av media|last1=Maron|first1=Marc|author1-link=Marc Maron|last2=Hendricks|first2=Christina|date=April 15, 2019|title=Episode 1010|work=[[WTF with Marc Maron]]|ref=harv|url=http://www.wtfpod.com/podcast/episode-1010-christina-hendricks}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Christina Hendricks}}\n* {{IMDb name|376716|Christina Hendricks}}\n* {{AllRovi person|329699|title=Christina Hendricks}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Christina Hendricks|Awards for Christina Hendricks]]\n|list  = \n{{Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Drama Supporting Actress}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwardsTVEnsembleDrama}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hendricks, Christina}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Idaho]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Actresses 