ez Marks]]\n*{{flagicon|United States}} [[Jim McGilvery]]\n*{{flagicon|United States}} {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Michael Ojo (basketball, born 1989)|Michael Ojo]]\n*{{flagicon|United States}} [[Otis Polk]]\n*{{flagicon|United States}} {{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Gerald Robinson (basketball, born 1984)|Gerald Robinson]]\n*{{flagicon|United States}} {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Cody Toppert]]\n*{{flagicon|United States}} [[Paul Williams (basketball)|Paul Williams]]\n*{{flagicon|United States Virgin Islands}} {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Jerome Gumbs]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[British Basketball League]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.plymouthraiders.com Official Plymouth Raiders website]\n*[http://www.facebook.com/plymouthraiders Plymouth Raiders] on [[Facebook]]\n*[https://twitter.com/officialraiders Plymouth Raiders] on [[Twitter]]\n*{{youtube|u=plymouthraiders|suffix='}}\n*[http://search.bbc.co.uk/cgi-bin/search/results.pl?scope=all&edition=d&tab=ns&recipe=all&q=%22plymouth+raiders%22&x=102&y=11 Plymouth Raiders news] from the [[BBC]]\n*[http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/plymouthraiders#axzz2LQJrhmMV Plymouth Raiders page at [[The Herald (Plymouth)|The Herald]]]\n\n{{British Basketball League teamlist}}\n\n[[Category:Basketball teams established in 1983]]\n[[Category:Plymouth Raiders]]\n[[Category:Basketball teams in England]]\n[[Category:Sport in Plymouth]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox basketball club\n| name            = Plymouth Raiders\n| logo            = File:Plymouth Raiders logo.png\n| imagesize       =  \n| sponsor         = \n| league          = [[British Basketball League|BBL]]\n| established     = {{Start date and age|1983}}\n| folded          =\n| history         = '''Plymouth Raiders'''  <br />(1983\u2013present)\n| arena           =  [[Plymouth Pavilions]]\n| capacity= 1,500 \n| location        = [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]]\n| coach           = [[Paul James (basketball)|Paul James]]\n| ownership       = BAU Global <br> Richard Mollard <br> Ross Mackenzie \n| director        =\n| website         = [http://www.plymouthraiders.com/ plymouthraiders.com]\n\n| h_pattern_b = _vneckwhite\n| h_body      = 075726\n| h_pattern_s = \n| h_shorts    = 075726\n\n| a_pattern_b = _vneckonwhite\n| a_body      = 075726\n| a_pattern_s = \n| a_shorts    = FFFFFF\n}}\n\nThe '''Plymouth Raiders''' are a professional [[basketball]] team based in [[Plymouth]], [[England]]. The team compete in the [[British Basketball League]], the country's premier basketball competition, and play their home games at the [[Plymouth Pavilions]]. The team's head coach is [[Paul James (basketball)|Paul James]].\n\nThe club was founded in 1983 through a merger between two local basketball clubs and went on to be the longest serving and most successful team in Division 1 of the [[English Basketball League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.millenniumhotels.co.uk/destinations/plymouth/events/enjoy-a-night-of-basketball-in-plymouth.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001030236/http://www.millenniumhotels.co.uk/destinations/plymouth/events/enjoy-a-night-of-basketball-in-plymouth.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 October 2015|title=Enjoy a night of basketball in Plymouth|publisher=Millennium Hotels|accessdate=29 September 2015}}</ref> Between 1996 and 2004, Plymouth Raiders won six different competitions, including three National Basketball League Play-off titles and the [[National Cup]] in 2004. \n\nAfter several years of dominating the EBL, in 2004 the Raiders moved up to the franchise-based British Basketball League, pitting themselves against the country's elite teams. To date their only success in the top-tier competition came in 2007, winning the [[BBL Trophy]], though the team has reached a further three Trophy and [[BBL Cup]] Finals since.\n\n==History==\n\n===Foundation and early years (1983\u20131996)===\nPlymouth Raiders' origins can be traced back to the mid-1970s with the original National League team Plymouth Panasonic, coached by future Raiders co-founder Frank Pocock ( age 82 of 2020 ) who entered national competition for the first and only time in 1979. Panasonic achieved a respectable 7th-place finish in Division Two before withdrawing during the close season due to a lack of finances, after which they were renamed Plymouth Kanaries and entered into the regional leagues in 1980. Deciding to have another attempt at establishing a National League club, Pocock along with local basketball figures Bob Karruck, Keith Mollard and businessman Les Palmer (of the [[Wrigley's]] company) formed a consortium in 1983 and merged the Kanaries with local rivals Plympton to form a new club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/Mollard-helped-create-original-blueprint-Raiders/story-16052012-detail/story.html|title=Mollard helped create original blueprint for Raiders to follow|publisher=[[The Herald (Plymouth)|The Herald]]|accessdate=29 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930233816/http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/Mollard-helped-create-original-blueprint-Raiders/story-16052012-detail/story.html|archive-date=30 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A sponsorship deal was arranged with pharmaceutical producer Glucodin and the team adopted their brand colours of red and yellow for their inaugural season in National League Division 2. Raiders played their first game on 1 October 1983 at the [[Mayflower Centre]], losing by one point, 75\u201376 to the visiting Merseyside Mustangs. After an inconsistent start to the campaign, coach Graham Nicholls stepped down from his position and was replaced by his assistant Karruck who led the team to lowly 10th-placed finished in their rookie season. {{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n[[Gary Stronach]] became player/coach in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/content/articles/2006/07/06/plymouth_raiders_news_july_2006.shtml|title=Stronach considers switch|date=22 June 2006|work=Plymouth Raiders news archive: June to September 2006|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=27 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe club endured a barren spell throughout the early 1990s and were forced to leave their Mayflower Centre in 1991 due to a leak in the roof. The team underwent a brief nomadic period using venues such as the John Kitto Centre, China Fleet Centre, Ivybridge Community College and even Torbay Leisure Centre, 30 miles away in [[Paignton]], to host home games. The Raiders returned to the Mayflower Centre, now with a brand new roof, in January 1992 and made a brief return to the Play-offs before bowing out to League Runners-up [[Bury Lobos]] in the Semi-final. By late 1992, with no major sponsor in place, the Raiders faced more financial troubles and an uncertain future. Following the help of a local newspaper campaign in the [[Evening Herald]], Wolferstan's Solicitors came forward with a sponsorship offer and investment that enabled the club to survive its second financial crisis in six years.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nIn the summer of 1993, head coach Bob Karruck announced his retirement and was replaced by his assistant Vic Flemming, who led the team to the 1994 National Trophy Final. Raiders were pitted against [[Sheffield Forgers (basketball)|Sheffield Forgers]] at their home [[Sheffield Arena]] and, despite a spirited performance, they lost by 60\u201362 to a Sheffield team who would be crowned as Carlsberg League champions the following year. Flemming's tenure lasted only a season and that summer he was replaced by long-serving player Gary Stronach, who assumed the role of player/coach.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n===Golden era (1996\u20132004)===\n[[File:PlymouthRaidersLogo.png|right|thumb|Plymouth Raiders Logo (used until 2012)]]\n\nIn 1998 the Raiders lost the league, trophy and NBL Final to [[Richmond Jaguars]].<ref>{{cite web| author = Mark Woods | title = Jaguars end era on high | url = http://www.britball.com/archive98/basketfest98_NBLMD1.html| year = | accessdate = 27 August 2016 | publisher = BritBall  }}</ref>\n\nThe 1998\u201399 season saw the Raiders and [[Solent Stars]] finishing the regular season on equal 21\u20135 records, the title was ultimately decided by a two-point aggregate differential in the head-to-head between the two teams.<ref>{{cite web| author = Mark Woods | title = Solent shoot for Stars with Div. 1 title | url = http://www.britball.com/archive99/solent-title99.htm | year = 1999 | accessdate = 2009-12-06 | publisher = BritBall  }}</ref> Raiders rallied a superb Play-off run and following the defeats of Cardiff Clippers, 111\u2013101, and Guilford Pumas, 93\u201375, they edged out familiar foes Teesside in the Final at [[Guildford Spectrum]], 71\u201366, securing the Play-off crown for the second time.<ref>{{cite web| author = Mark Woods | title = Stronach\u2019s men in Championship raid | url = http://www.britball.com/archive99/nblm1-final99.htm | year = 1999 | accessdate = 2009-12-06 | publisher = BritBall  }}</ref>\n\nThe 2000\u20132001 season saw Stronach recruit arguable the strongest roster the franchise had ever seen, bringing in [[Todd Cetnar]] and [[Terrence Durham]], two American imports straight out of [[University at Albany, SUNY|Albany]] and [[St. Bonaventure University]]\u2019s respectively. The addition of local players [[Roderick Wellington]], Deng Deng (brother of [[Luol Deng]]), Canadian Peter Knechtel and [[Wales|Welsh]] international Nathan Hayes, bolstered an impressive roster and with eight straight victories to open the season, the Raiders were on course to claim the newly rebranded NBL Conference title. The first defeat of the campaign came in the Trophy Semi-final to a [[Worthing Thunder]] team that inflicted two further defeats upon Plymouth throughout the season and matched the Raiders all the way in the hunt for silverware. However it was Raiders who came out on top with a 19\u20132 record and the Conference crown for the first time in the franchise's history. The season was completed with an excellent run in the Play-offs sweeping aside Sutton (98\u201368) and [[Manchester Magic]] (162\u2013155 over two games), before commanding an 83\u201377 defeat on Worthing at [[Wembley Arena]] and claiming the Championship double.<ref>{{cite web| author = Mark Woods | title = Plymouth delight Wembley hoardes | url = http://www.britball.com/2001/NBLMen-01-conffinal.html | year = 2001 | accessdate = 2009-12-06 | publisher = BritBall  }}</ref>\n\nAfter two seasons in Portugal, Terrence Durham's return was the only adjustment in a largely unchanged roster for the 2003\u20132004 season which saw the club accept an invitation to appear in the BBL Trophy for a second time, adding to a tough schedule including the league (now reverted to [[English Basketball League|EBL Division 1]]), the National Trophy and the National Cup, which for the first time in history didn't feature any BBL teams. Progress though the National Cup provided interest early in the season, and the Final was reached with Teesside Mohawks providing the opposition at the [[English Institute of Sport - Sheffield|EIS Sheffield]], however it was Raiders who walked away with the George Williams Trophy after a close 89\u201382 victory. The National Trophy was once more unattainable following a surprise defeat to Sutton in the semi-final, but Raiders domination in the league secured another trophy, finishing first with just two defeats to [[London United (basketball)|London United]] and Reading, who finished in second place. The Play-off Final was reached again, but Raiders were unable to add a third title to the season's haul as Teesside, exacting their National Cup defeat revenge, came out on top with an 80\u201375 win. {{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n===Move to the BBL and recent years (2004\u20132016)===\nHaving firmly established themselves as the dominant force in Division 1, the Plymouth board sought new challenges for the team and to expand the Raiders brand and during the summer of 2004 announced that they had been admitted into the top-tier BBL.<ref>{{cite news| author = Richard Taylor | title = Basketball season tips-off on positive note | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/basketball-season-tips-off-on-positive-note-550634.html | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = The Independent | location=London | date=2 October 2004}}</ref>\n\nDuring  the [[British Basketball League 2006-07|2006\u201307 season]] they won eight games in a row and by December found themselves joint top of the BBL.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Plymouth make it eight in a row | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/6178167.stm| accessdate = 2 May 2015 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=13 December 2006}}</ref> In the BBL Trophy final, at [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]]\u2019s [[MetroRadio Arena]] on 4 March 2007, Raiders defeated [[Newcastle Eagles]] 74\u201365 to win their first top-flight title.<ref>{{cite news| author = Rob Dugdale | title = Raiders lift BBL Trophy | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/6412079.stm | accessdate = 2 May 2015 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=4 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn the league, Raiders constantly held a Play-off position for the majority of the season and though qualifying with ease, just missed out on home advantage with a 5th place finish. A journey into uncharted territory awaited the Plymouth team appearing in their first BBL Play-offs, however it was also a long journey to face opponents [[Scottish Rocks]], as the league\u2019s most Southern and Northern teams met in the one-off clash. A dream first appearance to the [[BBL Finals Weekend|Finals Weekend]] for Raiders was dashed by a 6-point defeat, 83\u201377, but a huge worry was an in-game injury to captain Gavin Love\u2019s Achilles tendon, which subsequently forced the Point Guard to miss a call-up to the [[Great Britain national basketball team|Great Britain national team]].<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Guard Love re-signs with Plymouth | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/6903317.stm | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=17 July 2007}}</ref> At the end of season awards, Raiders \"big-man\" Aaron was named in the All-Star first team and 4th in the MVP ballot, finishing the season on 17 points-per-game, 12.4 rebounds-per-game and a field goal scoring average of 59%. On 1 May, the Raiders development programme was awarded with the prestigious Club Mark accolade by [[Sport England]] and [[England Basketball]].<ref>{{cite web | author =  | title = Club Mark Award | url = http://www.raidersdevelopment.com/news/may1stclubmark.htm | year = 2007 | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = Plymouth Raiders }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nWith such an excellent season under his belt, star man Carlton Aaron departed the team during the close-season, trying out for teams in [[South Korea]], before eventually signing for a Guildford side preparing for their first appearance in [[Europe]]\u2019s [[ULEB Cup]].<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Heat swoop for top centre Aaron | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/6913450.stm | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=24 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nAfter committing over two decades of service to the Raiders, Coach Stronach was presented by the [[BBC]] with a Lifetime Achievement Award at a ceremony in November, honouring the success he has brought to Plymouth.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Champion Harris handed BBC award | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/motorbikes/speedway/7113013.stm | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=26 November 2007}}</ref>  In March they travelled to leaders Newcastle, having won their previous seven league games.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders success needs recognition | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7304254.stm | accessdate = 24 September 2014 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=19 March 2008}}</ref>   They faced Newcastle in the 3rd place game on 4 May 2008, and though losing 54\u201333 at half-time, edged out their opponents in a tight 96\u201392 victory taking 3rd place, the best league position in the club's history.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders finish third in play-offs | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7384951.stm | accessdate = 24 September 2014 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=6 May 2008}}</ref>  With an average of 19 points-per-game, Plymouth\u2019s top scorer Andrew Lasker was named in the All-Star team for the [[British Basketball League 2007-08|2007\u201308 season]] .<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Lasker makes BBL All-Star squad | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7377098.stm | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=1 May 2008}}</ref>  After being declined by Newcastle and Guildford \u2013 who both finished above Plymouth in the league \u2013 [[FIBA]] approached Raiders with an invitation to compete in the [[EuroChallenge]] for the [[EuroChallenge 2008-09|2008\u201309 season]], which Raiders also duly declined.<ref>{{cite web | title = Raiders get green light from FIBA | url = http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/raiders/Raiders-green-light-FIBA/article-430776-detail/article.html | archive-url = https://archive.is/20130505123253/http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/raiders/Raiders-green-light-FIBA/article-430776-detail/article.html | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2013-05-05 | year = 2008 | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = The Herald }}</ref>\n\nAfter six years of sponsorship from Kularoos, the Raiders board announced during the summer of 2008 a major new deal had been reached with Plymouth-based chewing gum giant [[Airwaves (gum)|Wrigley\u2019s Airwaves]], reportedly \"one of the biggest in basketball history\".<ref>{{cite web | title = Pryce is right for new Raiders kit deal | url = http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/news/Pryce-right-new-Raiders-kit-deal/article-361464-detail/article.html | archive-url = https://archive.is/20130505141312/http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/news/Pryce-right-new-Raiders-kit-deal/article-361464-detail/article.html | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2013-05-05 | year = 2008 | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = The Herald }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| author = | title = New sponsorship deal for Raiders | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7560487.stm | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=14 August 2008}}</ref> The extra funds brought in allowed for a bigger budget in terms of recruiting, and within days the signing of [[Kwbana Beckles]] was publicised. Beckles came with plenty of pedigree having appeared in [[Sweden]], [[Switzerland]], [[Israel]] and spells for NBA teams [[Atlanta Hawks]] and [[Toronto Raptors]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Player Profile:Kwbana Beckles | url = http://www.basketballbeyondborders.com/Players%20Profile%20%20pages/Player_Profile_Kwbana%20Beckles.htm | year = 2008 | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = Basketball Beyond Borders | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110212163000/http://www.basketballbeyondborders.com/Players%20Profile%20%20pages/Player_Profile_Kwbana%20Beckles.htm | archivedate = 12 February 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders net ex-NBA star Beckles | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7569912.stm | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=19 August 2008}}</ref> Veteran player DeAntoine Beasley took up the new dual role as player/assistant coach, declining a coaching job in the USA<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Beasley agrees to stay at Raiders | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7463523.stm | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=20 June 2008}}</ref> while captain Gavin Love, who missed much of the previous season through injury signed a new one-year contract.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders agree new deal with Love | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7462888.stm  | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=19 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn October, the team was boosted with the visit of a [[FIBA]] inspection team that approved the use of the Pavilions for European competition matches, providing a top-two finish is achieved in the Championship.<ref name=\"Raiders given European approval\">{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders given European approval | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7694542.stm| accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=28 October 2008}}</ref> In the BBL Cup the Raiders won a two-game Semi-final series against Guildford to reach only their second BBL Final.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders reach Final with comeback | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7751620.stm| accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=26 November 2008}}</ref> Their final opponents were Everton Tigers who recorded a 103\u201349 victory over Plymouth at the NIA in Birmingham.<ref>{{cite news| author = Rob Dugdale | title = Tigers triumph in final demolition | url = https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/jan/18/basketball-bbl-cup-everton-tigers | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = The Guardian | location=London | date=18 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Garbelotto delighted with cup win | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7837873.stm| accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=19 January 2009}}</ref> At the end of January Coach Stronach announced the signing of [[Gerald Robinson (basketball, born 1984)|Gerald Robinson]], an American with a Dutch passport, from [[Spain|Spanish]] team Oviedo.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Plymouth Raiders seal new signing | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7857772.stm| accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=30 January 2009}}</ref> A week later, Gavin Love announced he was to retire from playing after 13 years with the Raiders, citing multiple injuries as the reason. In honour of his services to the club, his number six jersey was to be retired at a ceremony on 14 February 2009 prior to a game with Guildford.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Love calls time on Raiders career | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7875023.stm | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=6 February 2009}}</ref> [[Israel]]i Point Guard Haggai Hundert was drafted in from [[Slovenia]] to fill the void left by Love.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders sign Israeli point guard | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7887694.stm | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=13 February 2009}}</ref> The franchise expanded on its ambitions to play in Europe with the announcement on 16 March, of a co-operation deal with Spanish giants [[CB M\u00e1laga|Unicaja M\u00e1laga]]; the alliance will see Raiders coaches going to Spain to gain experience and young players coming to Plymouth to improve their English and education.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders link up with Spanish team | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7947532.stm| accessdate = 24 September 2014 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=17 March 2009}}</ref>  A 96\u201373 defeat at the hands of Sheffield Sharks saw injuries to Andrew Lasker, Anthony Martin and Terrence Durham.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Sheffield agony for the Raiders | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/7966054.stm | accessdate = 24 September 2014 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=28 March 2009}}</ref> In April 2009 it was announced that Andrew Lasker had made the team of the season.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Eagles guard Moore gets top award | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8022575.stm | accessdate = 24 September 2014| publisher = BBC Sport | date=28 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn summer 2009 Stronach revealed that the player's budget had been cut by 60\u201365% for the coming season, citing the economic climate and a lack of sponsorship as the main reasons for the cuts.<ref>{{cite web | title = We had to make cuts to secure Raiders\u2019 future | url = http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/news/make-cuts-secure-Raiders-future/article-1116641-detail/article.html | archive-url = https://archive.is/20130505073552/http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/news/make-cuts-secure-Raiders-future/article-1116641-detail/article.html | url-status = dead | archive-date = 5 May 2013 | year = 2009 | accessdate = 24 September 2014 | publisher = The Herald }}</ref> In June 2009 Allister Gall was named the new captain.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders promote Gall to captain | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8101151.stm | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=16 June 2009}}</ref> In July 2009 James Noel extended his contract.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Noel extends contract at Raiders| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8176871.stm | accessdate = 24 September 2014| publisher = BBC Sport | date=31 July 2009}}</ref> The summer saw the unveiling of a restructured development programme following a merger of Raiders development team with local club [[Plymouth Marjon Cannons]], headed by former Cannons coach George Hatchell.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders start new training scheme | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8154375.stm| accessdate = 24 September 2014 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=16 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nEric Flato, a recent graduate of [[Yale University]], was signed in July 2009,<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Plymouth capture Ivy League star | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8160541.stm | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=21 July 2009}}</ref> and the news was soon followed by the capture of Terry Horton, another American, who was brought in from Germany.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders announce Horton signing | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8163470.stm| accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=23 July 2009}}</ref> In October 2009 Anthony Martin was re-signed following a brief spell at Worcester, having departed the Raiders just months earlier.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Martin returns to Raiders squad| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8321042.stm| accessdate = 24 September 2014 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=23 October 2009}}</ref> Former Raiders development talent [[Anthony Rowe (basketball)|Anthony Rowe]] signed on a one-month deal in November.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Forward Rowe makes Raiders return| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8353397.stm| accessdate = 24 September 2014 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=11 November 2009}}</ref> Flato picked up a serious injury in November and subsequently left the club.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Flato leaves Raiders after injury| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8383364.stm | accessdate = 24 September 2014 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=28 November 2009}}</ref> His replacement was Drew Lasker, the team's top-scorer for the past four seasons, who left during the summer, but who had been without a club.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = American guard Drew Lasker rejoins Plymouth Raiders| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8388913.stm | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=2 December 2009}}</ref> He marked his return in a 69\u201384 loss to Everton on December 5.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Plymouth Raiders 69\u201384 Everton Tigers| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8395214.stm| accessdate = 2009-12-08 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=7 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn February it was announced that [[James Noel (basketball)|James Noel]] was released from his contract, due to a series of long-term injuries, allowing the team's bench players more opportunity.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = James Noel is released by Plymouth Raiders| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8508202.stm  | accessdate = 28 September 2010| publisher = BBC Sport | date=2 December 2009}}</ref> Form started to improve throughout the Spring, but a double loss to Glasgow and Worthing at the beginning of April ended any hopes of qualifying for the Play-offs with fives games left of the regular season.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Plymouth Raiders fail in Play-off bid| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8604937.stm  | accessdate = 28 September 2010 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=2 December 2009}}</ref> Two weeks later it was announced by the club that after 24 years of service Gary Stronach was to step down as head coach at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web| author = | title = Gary Stronach to quit as Plymouth Raiders coach| url = http://markbritball.blogspot.com/2010/04/gary-stronach-to-quit-as-plymouth.html | accessdate = 2010-04-15 | publisher = Britball }}</ref> Coming as a shock to many fans, Stronach cited the reason for his departure was that \"it's time for me to move on, broaden the horizon and see what's out there.\"<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Head coach Gary Stronach to leave Plymouth Raiders | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8623601.stm  | accessdate = 28 September 2010 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=2 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe club started preparations for the new season immediately and ushered in the new era post-Stronach with the appointment of former player and team captain [[Gavin Love]] as the new head coach of the Raiders' first team, stepping up from his previous position of Stronach's assistant coach.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Gavin Love appointed as Plymouth Raiders head coach | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8728079.stm  | accessdate = 28 September 2010 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=2 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| author = Mark Woods | title = Gavin Love confirmed as new Plymouth Raiders head coach | url = http://markbritball.blogspot.com/2010/06/gavin-love-confirmed-as-new-plymouth.html  | accessdate = 28 September 2010 | publisher = Britball | date=2 December 2009}}</ref> Love's first signing as head coach came in the form of dual-national American Guard Cody Toppert from [[Germany]].<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Plymouth Raiders boss Gavin Love makes first signing | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8742110.stm  | accessdate = 28 September 2010 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=2 December 2009}}</ref> His wife Brittany, a professional football player and United States international, followed him to Plymouth and signed for local team [[Plymouth Argyle L.F.C.|Plymouth Argyle Ladies]].<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Argyle Ladies set to sign US star Brittany Toppert | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/women/8758983.stm  | accessdate = 28 September 2010 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=2 December 2009}}</ref> Love continued to build the new-look Raiders roster with the signings of England international Taner Adu from [[Essex Pirates]]<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders snap up England star Taner Adu | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8753310.stm  | accessdate = 28 September 2010 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=2 December 2009}}</ref> and American import players Otis Polk and Brian McKenzie, straight out of college.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders snap up US guard Brian McKenzie | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8794675.stm  | accessdate = 28 September 2010 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=2 December 2009}}</ref> British youngsters Matt Guymon and Sam Cricelli were also drafted in soon after<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Raiders secure Sam Cricelli signing | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8879157.stm  | accessdate = 28 September 2010 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=2 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Plymouth Raiders sign point guard Matt Guymon | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8868917.stm  | accessdate = 28 September 2010 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=2 December 2009}}</ref> however England international Guymon left within weeks of the season opener for personal reasons.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Matt Guymon decides to leave Plymouth Raiders | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8964532.stm  | accessdate = 28 September 2010 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=2 December 2009}}</ref> With the announced returns of Marriott, Czynienik and Anthony Rowe from the previous season the roster was starting to take shape, but Love was dealt a further blow when fan-favourite [[Allister Gall]] announced he would not be renewing his contract for the upcoming campaign.<ref>{{cite news| author = | title = Allister Gall on course to depart Plymouth Raiders | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/basketball/8940995.stm  | accessdate = 28 September 2010 | publisher = BBC Sport | date=2 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== New owners (2017\u2013present) ===\nOn July 17, 2017 the ownership of Plymouth Raiders was taken over from Bob Widdecombe to Ross MacKenzie and Richard Mollard. The new owners moved quickly to appoint Louis Sayers as their first player for the [[2017\u201318 British Basketball League|2017\u201318 season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbl.org.uk/fan-favourite-sayers-first-sign-new-era-raiders/|title=Fan favourite Sayers first to sign in new era for Raiders|last=|first=|date=|website=British Basketball League|access-date=7 April 2018}}</ref> Following on from this, the owners introduced a brand new logo to form part of a re-branding of the club.\n\n==Logos==\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nImage:PlymouthRaidersLogo.png|<center>1996\u20132012</center>\nImage:PlymouthRaiders2012Logo.png|<center>2012\u20132017</center>\n</gallery>\n\n==Arena==\n[[File:PavilionsBasketball.jpg|right|thumb|Plymouth Pavilions arena]]\n\n::[[Mayflower Centre (Plymouth)|Mayflower Centre]] (1983\u20131996)\n::'''[[Plymouth Pavilions]]''' (1996\u2013present)\n\nPlymouth Raiders have played their home games at the [[Plymouth Pavilions]] arena since 1996. In basketball configuration the main arena has a capacity for 1,500 spectators, with tiered seating on either side of the court and floor-level seating behind each basket. {{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nBefore moving to the Pavilions, Raiders were based at the [[Mayflower Centre (Plymouth)|Mayflower Centre]], a 1,000-capacity sports facility adjacent to the [[Home Park]] football stadium in [[Central Park, Plymouth|Central Park]]. The Raiders played out of the Mayflower Centre from 1983 until their move to the Pavilions in 1996, however due to on-going issues with the venue's roof, the team spent much of the 1991\u20131992 season playing their home matches at the China Fleet Club, Ivybridge Community College, the John Kitto Centre and Torbay Leisure Centre in [[Paignton]]. {{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nThough the Pavilions arena has been approved by international governing body [[FIBA]] for hosting European competition matches,<ref name=\"Raiders given European approval\"/> former Raiders' chairman Bob Widdecombe has stated the club's ambition is to move to a new purpose-built arena that would be solely owned by the organisation<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/room-prima-donnas-Raiders/story-23023311-detail/story.html|title='No room for prima donnas at the Plymouth Raiders'|publisher=[[The Herald (Plymouth)|The Herald]]|accessdate=23 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925063008/http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/room-prima-donnas-Raiders/story-23023311-detail/story.html|archive-date=25 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and would be more suited to hosting European competition.<ref name=\"plymouthherald.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/Plymouth-Raiders-boss-interested-switch-Home-Park/story-19349914-detail/story.html|title=Plymouth Raiders boss is interested in a switch to Home Park ice rink arena|publisher=[[The Herald (Plymouth)|The Herald]]|accessdate=23 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925055240/http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/Plymouth-Raiders-boss-interested-switch-Home-Park/story-19349914-detail/story.html|archive-date=25 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Trophies==\n{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n===League===\n* '''NBL Conference Winners:''' 2000/01\n* '''EBL Division One Winners:''' 2003/04\n* '''NBL Division One Runners Up:''' 1996/97, 1997/98 & 1998/99\n* '''NBL Conference Runners Up:''' 2001/02, & 2002/03\n\n===Playoffs===\n* '''NBL Division One Play Off Winners:''' 1996/97, & 1998/99\n* '''NBL Conference Play Off Winners:''' 2000/01\n* '''EBL Division One Play Off Runners Up:''' 2003/04\n\n===Trophy===\n* '''National Trophy Runners Up:''' 1985/86, 1993/94, 1996/97, 1997/98 & 1998/99\n* '''BBL Trophy Winners:''' 2006/07\n* '''BBL Trophy Runners Up:''' 2011/12\n\n===Cup===\n* '''National Cup Winners:''' 2003/04\n* '''BBL Cup Winners' Cup Runners Up:''' 2007/08\n* '''BBL Cup Runners Up:''' 2011/2012\n\n==Season-by-season records==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-bgcolor=\"#efefef\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Division\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Tier\n!colspan=\"6\"|Regular Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Post-Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Trophy\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Head Coach\n|-\n! Finish\n! Played\n! Wins\n! Losses\n! Points\n! Win %\n|-\n|colspan=\"13\" align=center bgcolor=\"green\" | <span style=\"color:white\">'''Plymouth Raiders'''</span>\n|-\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1997\u201398 British Basketball League season|1997\u201398]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[English Basketball League|NBL1]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|II\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" bgcolor=silver|2nd\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|22\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|19\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|38\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|0.864\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Gary Stronach]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1998\u201399 British Basketball League season|1998\u201399]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[English Basketball League|NBL1]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|II\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" bgcolor=silver|2nd\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|26\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|21\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|42\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|0.808\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Gary Stronach]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1999\u20132000 British Basketball League season|1999\u201300]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[English Basketball League|NBL1]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|II\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|4th\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|24\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|16\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|style=\"text-align:c